# 🧠 Entorhinal Cortex

> **The entorhinal cortex is the primary gateway between the neocortex and the hippocampus — serving as the main input/output hub of the medial temporal lobe memory system and the first region to show neurofibrillary tangle pathology in Alzheimer's disease.**

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Hippocampus]] — receives perforant path input from EC layers II/III; EC is the main entry point to the trisynaptic circuit
- [[Limbic System]] — core component of the medial temporal lobe memory system
- [[Memory Systems]] — critical for encoding and retrieval of episodic and semantic memory
- [[Amygdala]] — reciprocal connections; emotional modulation of memory
- [[Cerebral Cortex]] — receives highly processed multimodal sensory info from association cortices
- [[Prefrontal Cortex]] — bidirectional connections for top-down memory modulation
- [[Olfaction]] — receives direct olfactory input (piriform cortex → EC); explains smell-triggered memories
- [[Neurodegenerative Diseases]] — Braak stage I-II: EC is the earliest site of tau pathology in AD

## 🗂️ Key Information

| Property | Detail |
|----------|--------|
| Location | Medial temporal lobe; posteromedial parahippocampal gyrus (anterior part) |
| Brodmann area | Area 28 (+ area 34 anteriorly) |
| Size | ~60 cm² in humans |
| Cytoarchitecture | Transitional (mesocortex): 6 layers but layer IV absent; island cells in layer II |
| Primary function | Gateway cortex: funnels neocortical information into hippocampus |
| Blood supply | Posterior cerebral artery (PCA); anterior choroidal artery |

