## 🔑 Connectivity — Information Flow

### Input to Hippocampus (Cortical → Hippocampal)
```
Neocortical association areas (visual, auditory, somatosensory, prefrontal)
    ↓
Perirhinal cortex (area 35/36) + Parahippocampal cortex (area TH/TF)
    ↓
Entorhinal Cortex (layers II/III)
    ↓ Perforant Path (layers II → dentate gyrus)
    ↓ Temporoammonic Path (layers III → CA1/subiculum directly)
Hippocampus (trisynaptic circuit)
```

### Output from Hippocampus (Hippocampal → Cortical)
```
CA1 + Subiculum
    ↓
Entorhinal Cortex (layers V/VI)
    ↓
Perirhinal + Parahippocampal cortices
    ↓
Widespread neocortex (memory storage/retrieval)
```

### Grid Cells (Medial EC)
- Discovered by Moser & Moser (Nobel Prize 2014, shared with O'Keefe)
- MEC layer II/III neurons fire at multiple spatial locations forming a **hexagonal grid pattern**
- Provide a **metric coordinate system** for spatial navigation
- Work in concert with [[Hippocampus]] place cells (O'Keefe) and head direction cells
- Grid cell spacing and orientation are consistent within a module, vary between modules

### Perforant Path
- **Main cortical input to hippocampus**
- Axons of EC layer II cells perforate the subiculum → reach dentate gyrus and CA3
- Lateral perforant path (LEC): to outer molecular layer of dentate
- Medial perforant path (MEC): to middle molecular layer of dentate
- Temporoammonic path: EC layer III → CA1 (bypasses dentate/CA3 — "direct" path)

